THIRD-PARTY ATTRIBUTIONS

The following third-party materials were referenced during development.
None are included in this distribution. All are cited for attribution only.

---

1. Microsoft KMDF Driver Samples
   Source: https://github.com/microsoft/Windows-driver-samples
   License: MIT
   Used: firefly.c (DriverEntry/EvtDriverDeviceAdd patterns),
         kbfiltr/moufiltr (lower-filter installation patterns),
         bthhid sample (BRB completion routine reference).
   Note: Driver code structure follows Microsoft sample conventions.
   No Microsoft sample source is copied verbatim; the patterns are
   referenced as architectural guides.

2. Linux hid-magicmouse.c
   Source: https://github.com/torvalds/linux
   Path: drivers/hid/hid-magicmouse.c
   License: GPL-2.0-only
   Used: Read-only algorithm reference for Report ID 0x12 (multi-touch
   report) byte layout and scroll translation logic. The Linux implementation
   provided the field offsets (X, Y, touch size, tracking ID, touch state)
   used to design M12's InputHandler.c. No GPL source is copied or linked
   into this distribution. M12 is an independently-written Windows kernel
   driver that implements equivalent functionality under MIT license.

3. MagicMouse2DriversWin11x64 (applewirelessmouse.sys)
   Source: https://github.com/tealtadpole/MagicMouse2DriversWin11x64
   (also distributed as AppleWirelessMouse64 in Apple Boot Camp packages)
   Used: Architectural baseline reference. The INF hardware ID list and
   device topology (BTHENUM HID COL01/COL02 split) were studied as the
   reference implementation for understanding the Windows HID stack for
   Apple Magic Mouse. The driver binary is not redistributed.
   Note: Apple is the original author. The tealtadpole distribution adds
   PID 0x0323 support to the original Boot Camp INF.

4. applewirelessmouse.sys (original Apple Inc.)
   The binary at offset 0xa850 (116-byte HID descriptor) was analyzed
   via Ghidra for byte layout reference. No Apple proprietary code is
   included in this distribution.

5. MagicUtilities / MagicMouse.sys
   Source: https://magicutilities.net (Rain9333)
   Used: Reverse-engineering reference only, under DMCA 17 U.S.C. ss 1201(f)
   (interoperability exception), Canada Copyright Act ss 30.61, and EU
   Software Directive 2009/24/EC Article 6. The analysis was conducted to
   understand KMDF API usage patterns, BRB interception, and HID descriptor
   mutation techniques for the purpose of building an interoperable
   independent implementation (M12). The MagicUtilities binary is not
   redistributed. No MagicUtilities source is copied.

6. WDK / EWDK (Windows Driver Kit / Enterprise WDK)
   Source: https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-hardware/drivers/
   License: Microsoft Software License Terms (build tools only)
   Used: Build environment (EWDK 25H2, Build 26100.6584) for compiling
   and verifying the M12 kernel driver. The EWDK build toolchain is not
   redistributed; it is a development-time dependency only.

7. WinMagicBattery
   Source: https://github.com/hank1101444/WinMagicBattery
   License: MIT
   Used: Confirmed the HID Input Report 0x90 battery reading approach
   (COL02 collection, byte[2] = battery %) as a working pattern on
   Windows. No code is copied; the project validated the feasibility of
   the approach used in MagicMouseTray.

